[2]
Date: Sat, 3 May 1997 12:46:13 +0700 (GMT)
From: "Nelia P. Salazar " <alnps@diamond.mahidol.ac.th>
Simon Elliott's comments on the multifarious sources of environmental stress
that could have led to the extinction of prehistoric species is consistent
with synecology.
Just to add another dimension to the disease theory, a parasite or pathogen
will not kill its host if it were to survive indefinitely. This relationship
is seen in chronic helminthic infections or in slow, persistent viral
infections. Fatal opportunistic infections in man, for instance, represent
the case of an "old parasite" in a "new host", eg, toxoplasmosis in AIDS or
human intestinal capillariasis. Evidently, HIV overdid itself in attacking a
strategic component of host resistance while annihilating its prospective
host. (It should have known better as those prehistoric "viroids" or whatever).
---
Nelia P. Salazar
